<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Again, what is this issue boiling down to? That there should be punishment for letting people onto the rotation? <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
The issue is not punishing people for letting others onto the rotation. The issue IS that by not maintaining an orderly progression through a rotation, those who are obeying the rotation will not see their turn, or at least have a much longer delay in seeing their turn. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
If some guild can get onto the rotation that is the entire reason the rotation is there. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
No. The rotations are not in place to allow every guild a shot at a mob, as they want it. <br>
<br>
The rotations are in place to allow every guild who is on the rotation an EQUAL amount of exposure to that mob, an equal window of time in which to kill the mob. <br>
<br>
Other guilds that get on, do so through concession or race. A race is still a race, even if one driver doesn't turn the car on. They just lose the race by *a lot* instead of a little.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
The simple fact some several guilds happen to get on at once is immaterial<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Excepting that the entire point of this discussion is about guilds entering the rotation all in one place. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
and whining about it is the attitude of someone unwilling to share. Your guild brought it up, and I ask again, why?<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
As they were next in line, they were watching the kill times more closely than others. You can be damn sure, that if a guild let people into the rotation before them constantly before my guild's turn on sev, I'd say &quot;boo&quot; as well. Not limiting content to the guilds entering the rotation is great, and not limiting content to the generous guild is great, but restricting the access to, and pushing back each person's turn on the rotation is *not* great. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
What is wrong with 3 guilds getting on the rotation? Do you understand the point of the rotation? It is to give everyone an equal opportunity at a mob that many want to kill. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
There is nothing wrong with three more guilds on the rotation. The point of the rotation, however, is not to let guilds in, until every guild on the server that *can* kill Sev, is on the rotation. The point of the rotation, as you said, is to offer equal opportunity at a mob that many want to kill. Each time the mob's spawn is pushed back a week for a guild because more people got on the rotation, that is a week in which the guild is restricted from attempting that content. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Complaining because several guilds were allowed to slip in at the same point is complaining about having to share. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
This is wrong, on it's face. A guild that comes in and says &quot;We respect the rotations, and agree that they should be there, but we'd like our turn as well&quot; is OBVIOUSLY not complaining about sharing, but complaining about the *lack* of sharing. Equal turns means 'equal turns'. It is about the opposite of complaining about sharing. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Why is CoN special in this case? Or more pertinently, why is the guild on deck for a mob special compared to every other guild on the rotation? Guild #6 down the road will also have to wait 3 more spawns due to these guilds getting in. Do you think that just because your turn is getting close you somehow have a greater right to a mob?<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I would suggest that your hostility is unwarrented on the general boards. I would also suggest that Guild #6 down the road would be naturally less aware of spawn times, and of kill times as a guild that is trying to plan their own attempt on Sev. Frankly, it doesn't matter to me when the guild right after Clan Bashemded kills Sev, or Doze, or Zlandicar. However, the time the guild right BEFORE ours kills the mob we are up for, matters a lot, and we watch it as closely as we can. <br>
<br>
I would suggest that the reason other people didn't post, is because they didn't *know* since the sev rotation is so long, that three more guilds had entered, and their turns had been pushed back by three weeks. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
The idea of instating rules limiting the number of guilds able to slip in, and rules punishing those by forcing a pass that either lose a race or let multiple guilds in goes against the very fabric of what the rotations mean. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
If this is your point of view, and you won't change your mind, I understand. <br>
<br>
However, you are in error. The very fabric of the rotations is to allow an environment in which people can be reasonably sure they will get an attempt at a mob in an equal number of times as others. Arguably, those who concede or do not move on a mob and have people enter the rotation before them are taking a disproportionate amount of time on their turn. <br>
<br>
It is not a system by which people are meant to hold each other's hand, and to have no urgency to kill a mob because they are on rotation: A rotation is a promise that you will have a chance to kill a mob, once you've proved that you can already. <br>
<br>
I know for a FACT that when our next Dozekar comes up, that we will move on him as soon as he pops; we had to pass our last due to the holiday weekend, and be damnned if we're going to let someone in front of us and push our turn back another week. Is *that* against the spirit of the rotation? No, it's not. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Those are attempts at limiting content from people in order to keep the interval between kills for those already on the rotation shorter. That is NOT acceptable.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
The rotations are in place to do exactly this already. Realize that the mobs, if left FFA, would be met with speed and reckless abandon by those guilds who would want to get as much per day, or per patch day, as possible. that means the big guilds would be eating and otherwise owning every spawn they could, if mobs were not on rotation. <br>
<br>
Rotations are in place to make sure there is a fair, and even, and also SPEEDY progression through the list in order, so that everyone gets an equal shot. (Speed is relative to the size of the rotation, but the point is the same). That is why we enforce a 24 hour window. The idea of 'shit or get off the pot' is already written into our rules. Your perception of acceptability is incorrect, as is your assumption that this would be done to limit content. Limiting content is having a guild in a voluntary rotation and then effectively delaying their access in perpetuity, as could be done if a guild was so inclined. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Whether or not you are understanding the implications of the discussion on this or not, I won't hazard a guess, but the fact is it is in the same spirit as the earlier topid on removing sev from the rotation. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I believe you have missed the point, and as such, should not cast aspirsions on someone else's ability to understand the implications of this discussion. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
People thinking their &quot;right&quot; to some mob is great enough they should be able to somehow limit how often others get a chance to kill it in order to get themselves a chance more than once per 3 months.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
You could be writing about the opposite side of this, you understand, with that statement. CoN, and all the guilds after, have as much right to as regular a Sev kill as anyone else. Moreso, I would claim, because they have agreed to enter into a voluntary rotation. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
There is no compromise. Rotations are there to allow *ANYONE* with the power and willingness to have a chance at content, and to give everyone that can kill the mob an equal chance at killing it and preventing monopolization. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Again, your statements could be written from the opposite point of view. Isn't an equal chance, an equal chance? Shouldn't then, all guilds have their one shot per spawn cycle, and if they can't, no matter if they've lost a race or conceded the mob, shouldn't they be forced to pass, for an &quot;equal&quot; shot?<br>
<br>
Be careful what you wish for: our system is balanced, and allows leeway that true equality wouldn't. Forward momentum must be maintained, or it's not a rotation. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
That is the essence of the rotation. That and giving guilds a window in which to kill mobs (24 hours) so that we all don't have to spend our lives at the keyboard ready to jump on mob x just so we have a chance to kill it once in awhile. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
However, when a mob is predictable, it is not too much to ask that a guild up for their turn be able to kill, and proceed to kill, the mob. Plan for the mob up at server up, which is what we did to get on the rotation. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
The complaints and suggestions on ways to &quot;keep the rot moving&quot; as it was put go against the spirit of the rotation system, an attempt to limit access to content.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
You are incorrect. Maintaining a working rotation is the ONLY thing that is in the spirit of the rotation. Frankly, any rotation I ever get on, if it doesn't move closer to our turn in three or four weeks, I'll be here suggesting it be taken off rotation, since to HAVE a rotation, it needs to ROTATE through the guilds that are up. Trying to invalidate valid claims and suggestions by labelling them as detrimental to the rotation system is not a factually valid argument. You give no reasons, nor any support to the claim that making people pass after 2 spawn cycles without killing the mob is limiting content: there are two opportunities for a guild to kill their mob. If anything, that is generous, and promotes *less* racing. <br>
<br>
There is no attempt to limit content here: in fact, we are suggesting new ways to make sure that content gets spread to those who are chomping at the bit for it, and gets to everyone in time. <br>
<br>
At any rate, I have factually and logically addressed your points about the problems with my suggestion, and I believe it still stands. If you agree or disagree, is no longer my concern. <br>
<br>
If you have new issues to raise, I'll address them as well. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>After a guild has lost a race twice, or passed voluntairily on their turn to another guild twice, that guild should, I think, be asked or forced to pass their turn to the next guild. </strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
It gives a period of time equal to two spawn cycles to the guild in question to kill the mob in question, and maintains a forward cycle through the guilds up for a mob. Besides, if it is so enormously hard to kill a mob within those two spawn cycles, everyone will face that same hardship, and be forced to pass, moving the rotation faster through anyway, and the guild's turn will come up again quickly anyway. <br>
<br>
Yers,<br>
<br>
